<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security on UK Polling Day to Counter IRA Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Unprecedented security measures
are to be taken on polling day, May 1st, all over Britain to
thwart any attempt by the Irish Republic Army (IRA) to disrupt the
general election.
</P>
<P>
45,000 polling stations are to be searched for explosive
devices, extra police officers posted and some voters may be
searched according to a security plan by Home Office released here
today.
</P>
<P>
The plan was made as West Midlands police announced that two
small bombs had exploded in the rush hour at 100ft pylon by the M6
near Walsall on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police said the terrorists had come close to causing "total
devastation" and loss of life after a device blew up two of the
four legs of a 132,000 volt electricity pylon.
</P>
<P>
Home Office sources said they had no intelligence about a
specific IRA threat but recent IRA activity had given cause for
concern and there was no reason to think that the terrorists would
respect the importance of the coming election.
</P>
<P>
A senior security official said: "It is clear that the IRA's
campaign is focused on generating publicity by causing maximum
disruption at minimum risk to itself."
</P>
<P>
Home Office intends to impose tight security measures on the
polling day to avoid further disruption by the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Among the precautions is the decision by the Home Office to
send all 659 acting returning officers a circular telling them how
to respond to an attack.
</P>
<P>
It says: "Provided that an adequate security plan, based on
police advice, has been put in place, it should possible to avoid
major disruption, such as evacuation of premises, in almost all
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"Should a bomb-threat be received, the police will assess its
credibility and consider, in the light of the security measures in
place, what level of response is appropriate."
</P>
<P>
"Their aim will be to enable the electoral process to continue
uninterrupted unless that would pose a clear risk to public
safety," it adds.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, launched its election
manifesto in Northern Ireland yesterday by saying that a vote for
its candidates would help to "tip the balance towards real peace".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
