<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Beats Germany in Ice Hockey Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Titleholders the Czech Republic
rallied from behind to beat Germany 2-1 in their opening game at
World Ice Hockey Championships on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Vujtec set up two goals in the last 15 minutes to save
the day for the Czechs, who had failed to outsmart German
goalkeeper Joseph Heiss in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
Germany took the lead on a power play in the second period,
defenceman Mirko Ludemann scoring with just eight seconds left of
Ladislv Benysek's two-minute penalty for holding.
</P>
<P>
In the third period, the Czechs strung together the kind of
strings of passes that had eluded them in the opening 40 minutes,
though they were still but a shadow of the side who won gold in
Vienna last year.
</P>
<P>
Martin Prochazka found the net in the 46th minute, slamming the
puck home at the far post from a pass by Vujtek. The tired German
defence were in tatters.
</P>
<P>
With less than five minutes to play, Vujtek and Roman Simicek
broke through the German rearguard and Simicek scored the winner
virtually unchallenged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
