<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: UN Move on Israel Good Score for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today hailed a U.N. General
Assembly resolution demanding an immediate halt to Israeli
settlements activities as a good score both for the Palestinians
and the world body.
</P>
<P>
"All states that voted in favor of the resolution, those
abstained and even the U.S. have criticized and rejected building
the Israeli settlements," Egypt's permanent delegate to the United
Nations Nabil el-Arabi said in statements quoted by the Egyptian
MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
The resolution passed in an overwhelming vote of 134-3, with 11
abstentions, at a special emergency session Thursday, urged an end
to all forms of assistance and support for illegal Israeli
activities in the occupied territories, especially settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. General Assembly resolution stressed the necessity of
halting aid to countries that have institutions, individuals or
firms work in building those settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe all countries will take that into consideration," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Assistant Foreign Minister for International Legal
Affairs Hussein Hassouna said the resolution came in "the
framework of the assembly's missions of maintaining world peace
and security and in accordance with the U.N. Charter."
</P>
<P>
"The resolution stressed again that the U.N. is the main forum
for discussing the Palestinian issue and following up its
developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian delegate to the United Nations Nasser
Qidwa today hailed the resolution as a very strong reaction to the
Israeli settlement operations.
</P>
<P>
"It is one of the strongest resolutions by the General Assembly
demanding an immediate halt to Israel's construction of a new
settlement in East Jerusalem," Qidwa told the Egyptian Voice of
Arab radio.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reiterated that the 185-member General Assembly,
if necessary, may meet once again on the Israeli settlement
activities, Qidwa added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called for setting up a mechanism to report
to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan within two months the latest
developments of the peace process, so that the assembly can decide
on what step to be taken next.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the Arab states to move effectively if Israel
insisted on going ahead with "political confrontation."
</P>
<P>
The resolution of the General Assembly, approved despite
negative votes from the U.S., Israel and Micronesia, demanded
"immediate and full cessation of the construction... and of all
other Israeli settlement activities."
</P>
<P>
Israel began the Har Homa construction on March 18 despite
strong Palestinian protests and international pressure. The peace
process has since grounded to a halt, leading to violent clashes
between Palestinian stone-throwers and Israeli soldiers across the
Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
