<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Longest Tunnel to Be Completed Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The would-be longest tunnel in
Pakistan is set to be completed late May , one month ahead of
schedule, a Chinese engineer said today at Batkhela, about 300
kilometers northwest of here.
</P>
<P>
"We've excavated 710 meters just this month into the mountain,
bringing to 2868.4 meters the total length of the tunnel we've
already completed," said Zhao Guangfa, manager of China
Geo-engineering corp., which has been undertaking the project
since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
"With the present highest speed, we're sure that we can finish
another 500 meters left by May 25," Zhao said at the entrance of
the tunnel located in a mountain near the Pathan village of the
Malakand Agency in North West Frontier province.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that the Pakistani authorities would
continue to enhance their cooperation with the Chinese engineers
to ensure a smooth completion of the tunnel, which will greatly
benefit the country's agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
The 3382-meter-long tunnel is the bottleneck of a grand
salinity control and reclamation project in the province.
</P>
<P>
The construction of upper Swat canal diversion and tunnel
works, financed by the Asian Development Bank and Swiss
Development Cooperation, falls in the areas of Swabi, Mardan and
Charsadad districts as well as in Malakand Agency of the NWFP.
</P>
<P>
The project covers an area of about 281,300 acres, which, like
other parts of the country, is affected by the menace of
waterlogging, salinity and frequent flooding due to overflowing of
the natural drains, which have significantly affected crop growth
in the region.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that upon completion of the project, crop
yields in the area will be almost doubled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
