<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sponsored AIDS Trials Could Be Lethal: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Some of the AIDS research
programs being conducted by the United States government among
women in poor countries could result in as many as 1,000 children
dying unnecessarily from HIV infections.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by the Consumers International regional
office for Africa here today, adding that some of the female HIV
carriers undergoing medical experiments are given either placebos
or drugs that have not been proven effective, instead of the AZT
drug that has proved to slow down the spread of the virus.
</P>
<P>
It said these experiments are taking place in Burkina Faso,
Cote d'Ivoire, Kenya, Malawi, Uganda, Tanzania, Thailand,
Zimbabwe and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
"The American government is paying for experiments on African,
Asian and Caribbean women which would never be tolerated in this
country. It is a clear cut double standard and for these babies
it will be lethal," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said public health experts strongly objected to trials that
denied women access to any intervention already proved effective,
such as AZT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-26 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Help Its Companies to Compete in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 26 (Xinhua)-- The U.S. government will help
American telecom companies to compete in a
multi-billion-U.S. dollar market in the Middle East, a top
U.S. official said here today.
</P>
<P>
" We want our companies to have every (business) opportunity in
the region's telecommunications market," said Larry Irving,
Assistant Secretary of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
" We will provide (the region's partners)information about our
companies and provide our companies with information about
opportunities," he said, adding:" We will serve to make sure the
parties to talk to each other."
</P>
<P>
Larry made the remarks at a press conference before the Midcom
97 takes place here from April 27 to 29.
</P>
<P>
He is leading a 33-strong delegation of U.S. government
officials and senior telecom executives to participate in the
conference, the third of its kind held in the Gulf Arab country.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to focus on ways of securing funds
for multi-billion-dollar projects in the communications sector in
Saudi Arabia, Iran and other Middle East states.
</P>
<P>
The projects are designed to expand the existing networks and
set up new telephone ventures.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the conference estimate that the Middle East
needs to spend some 30 billion dollars in the next few years to
upgrade its telecom network to face growing needs.
</P>
<P>
Fierce competition are expected between regional and global
telecom companies as they race for footholds in the region, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Larry said the U.S.government will help American companies in
the race, but will not extend "specific" political and commercial
support to American participators.
</P>
<P>
"There is no specific support of these kinds and what we do is
to bring them (business parties related) to negotiation tables,
and the actual work will be done by our companies," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official also said that in the race, the Gulf region
will form the centerpiece of the business battle because Gulf
governments are pressing for urgent improvement of their telecom
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
According to the Inter-Arab Corporation for Investment
Guarantee, the Gulf Cooperation Council(GCC) states will have to
pump nearly 13 billion dollars into communications projects by
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman and
the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
