<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city will add 100 supermarkets and 200 chain stores
this year to its 2,400-plus service outlets of this kind.
</P>
<P>
It will also welcome overseas counterparts to join the market
competition.
</P>
<P>
The city's sales in this sector reached eight billion
yuan-worth last year, accounting for nearly seven percent of
consumer goods retail; the 60-odd chain stores belonging to four
foreign supermarket companies accounted for an 18 percent share of
the total sales, said Li Shuxiang, a local official.
</P>
<P>
The city will give top priority this year to ensuring the
quality, scale and distribution of chain stores, and reduce its
current 40 chain store companies to 20 to form more efficient
groups through merger and optimization of assets disposition.
</P>
