<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Elections Start in Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni voters went to the polls
starting 8 a.m. (local time) today in all Yemeni provinces to
elect their deputies to the new 301-member house of
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni media described popular response to the parliamentary
elections as enthusiastic. About 4.64 million of the country's 16
million population were registered to vote. The registered voters
lined up from day-break in the 301 constituencies which embraced
2,071 election centers manned by some committees throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The number of Candidates competing for the house stood at
2,311, of whom 754 are party nominees, and 1,557 independent
ones. There are 20 women among the candidates.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary elections are contested by 12 parties for 301
seats, including the ruling People's Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
Four parties are boycotting the elections -- namely, the Yemen
Socialist Party, the Unionist Grouping Party, the League of
Yemenites and the Union of Popular Forces.
</P>
<P>
The elections, the first since a two-month civil war in 1994,
are attracting extensive Arab and world attention.
</P>
<P>
Some 141 international observers are supervising the elections,
including Arab observers from Palestine, Sudan and Egypt, and
other observers from the European Union, the United Nations, the
U.S., Russia, Scandinavian countries and Poland.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 22,000 voluntary local observers belong to various
non-governmental organizations. A large number of Arab and foreign
journalists are covering the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
