<HEADLINE> "WB Loans to Xiaolangdi Dam Project More Cost-Effective" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank loans used for
part of the Xiaolangdi Dam project have been more fruitful in a
broader sense as they have accelerated China's efforts to get on
the internationally advanced track in terms of managerial system
and concepts."
</P>
<P>
Wang Xianru, director of the Yellow River Water and Hydropower
Development Corporation (YRWHDC), made this remark during an
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Hydraulic Project, now under construction on the
Yellow River, near this city in central China's Henan Province, is
the second-largest of its kind in China, only after the gigantic
Three Gorges Hydropower Project on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
According to Zou Yuanqin, chief of the Planning Division, the
Xiaolangdi project plans to use 1.19 billion US dollars of World
Bank loans, including 890 million US dollars in hard loans and 190
million US dollars in export credits for purchase of equipment,
and 110 million US dollars in soft loans for the relocation of
local residents in the project area.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of World Bank loans, about 460 million US
dollars, has been allocated appropriately, and the two sides are
expected to discuss the arrangements for the second group, about
430 million US dollars, in May.
</P>
<P>
As required by the bank, international methods of tendering,
management and supervision have been adopted in the whole process
of the project, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the project has been contracted by three
multinational consortiums, and the Chinese side has learned
advanced experience and technical knowhow regarding management and
technology.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeatedly urged our men to foster their 'sense of
contract', that is, to do everything strictly in line with the
contract," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, Chinese contractors must learn the art of
insisting on compensation for dereliction of contract requirements
and learn to make written reports.
</P>
<P>
He praised foreign companies involved in the project for the
quality and efficiency of their staff and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and foreign managers and technicians have learned from
one another over the past few years of cooperation, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
