<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colorful Ceremony Marks Opening of HK's Lantau Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's newest landmark,
the 3.5 kilometer Lantau Link, was officially opened in a colorful
ceremony here this evening.
</P>
<P>
The Link comprises two bridges -- the 2.2 kilometer-long Tsing
Ma Bridge, which is of suspension structure, and the
820-meter-long Kap Shui Mun Bridge, which is cable-stayed -- and
the 503-meter Ma Wan connecting viaduct.
</P>
<P>
The Lantau Link, one of the 10 projects in the 156.4 billion HK
dollars (20 billion U.S. dollars) Hong Kong Airport Core Program,
for the first time links Hong Kong's largest island of Lantau with
Kowloon. It will play a key role in providing road and rail link
to the new airport which, now still under construction, is
scheduled to open in April next year.
</P>
<P>
Throughout its 3.5-kilometer length, the double-deck Lantau
Link has six road lanes on the open upper deck and two road lanes
for use in bad weather, or in an emergency, on the sheltered lower
deck, which will also carry the railway for the new airport.
</P>
<P>
With a main span of 1,377 meters, Tsing Ma is the longest span
suspension road-rail bridge in the world -- more than twice the
length of the Sydney harbor Bridge. Its total length of wire in
the suspension cables measuring at 160,000 kilometers, is enough
to circle the world four times.
</P>
<P>
Its deck is 62 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
Kap Shui Mun, with a main span of 430 meters, is the world's
longest cable-stayed bridge to carry both road and rail traffic.
And its deck is 47 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony also featured such activities as a land
parade by community groups representing Hong Kong's 18 districts,
a car procession, a fly-past by airplanes and helicopters, a
flotilla of vessels, lighting up of the Link and a 20-minute
fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the ceremony were more than 1,200 guests
including former British prime minister Margaret Thatcher, Hong
Kong Governor Chris Patten, Chief Secretary Mrs. Anson Chan and
representatives from the both sides on the Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
