<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Returns Home After Brief Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
returned home this afternoon from a Gulf tour that took him to
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia to discuss the stalled Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The president, accompanied on his tour by several ministers and
aides, made no statement upon his return. He last visited Saudi
Arabia in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Saudi King Fahd today dwelt on coordination of
Arab stances in the Mideast peace march and the recent Arab and
Islamic drive to save the process.
</P>
<P>
At the start of his lightning visit, Mubarak stopped in Kuwait
Saturday and held talks with Amir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed
al-Sabah on the setbacks of the Mideast peace. It is his fourth
visit to Kuwait since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said Mubarak's undeclared visit to the two
countries was designed to gain Arab support for an expanded or
mini summit to salvage the peace process from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mubarak said that Egypt was ready to host a
mini-summit grouping Syria, Jordan, Egypt and the Palestinian
National Authority to restart the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, however, said he opposed holding an Arab summit at
present for fear it could further complicate the peace talks by
taking collective measures against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks ground to a halt last month after Israel
started construction of a new Jewish settlement in disputed Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries decided to freeze all normalization process
with the Jewish state at a foreign ministers' meeting here
afterwards. 
