<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Sea Access Taking Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- With the completion of the
track-laying of the Nanning-Kunming Railway, which links up the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Guizhou and Yunnan provinces,
access to the sea for Southwest China has been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The new access benefits Yunnan, Guizhou, Sichuan and Hunan
provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, as well as
the western part of Guangdong Province, covering nearly one sixth
of China's total 9.6 million sq km and with a total population of
over 200 million.
</P>
<P>
Highways, railways and air routes now link up all parts of the
region, and construction of ports along the coast of the South
China Sea is going full speed ahead. A total of 50 billion yuan
has been invested in such undertakings.
</P>
<P>
The progress has come in the wake of a suggestion by the State
Council in 1992 that access to the sea for the southwest area,
centered around the Nanning-Kunming Railway, should be improved to
promote trade and economic cooperation with Southeast Asia, Hong
Kong and Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
