<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authorities to Step up Checks on Value of Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Two government departments plan
to jointly check up on the value of overseas investments in the form
of material objects, in order to prevent the unlawful practices of
overevaluating or underevaluating.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made when officials from the State Bureau of
Commodity Inspection and the General Administration of Customs
met in Jinhua City, in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, in 1996 the commodity
inspection authorities examined 7,568 batches of foreign
investments in kind, which were reportedly valued at a total of
4.27 billion US dollars. But the value went down by 310 million US
dollars after the inspection was made.
</P>
<P>
Last year China's Customs Service collected a total of 85
billion yuan in duty from imports of foreign-invested assets.
But examination resulted in the recovery of another 2.6
billion yuan for the state exchequer.
</P>
<P>
However, the departments said, the inspection covered only a
small proportion of assets related to foreign investments. Last
year a mere 17 percent of the investments in kind -- totaling
24.86 billion US dollars -- were scanned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
