<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB-Funded Dam Brings International Expertise to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Xiaolangdi Dam being built on
the Yellow River, the second-largest river in China, will not only
give China a multipurpose dam, it will give it a scenic reservoir
with tourism potential, and greater ability to control the
turbulent Yellow River and irrigate a larger area of farmland.
</P>
<P>
It will also facilitate training a contingent of Chinese
managerial and technical personnel with expertise learned from
hundreds of foreign experts.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xianru, deputy director of the Yellow River Water and
Hydropower Development Corporation (YRWHDC), told Xinhua that the
project plans to introduce over one billion US dollars in loans
from the World Bank, which will make it rank the first among all
Chinese projects in terms of the amount borrowed from the
international financial institution.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is reckoned to be particularly challenging
in engineering terms, is considered to be the best place for
training Chinese managerial and technical personnel for water
projects in an international environment, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese managers and technicians can learn a lot from the World
Bank officials who visit the site twice a year, Canadian
consultants who are assigned to the site to supervise the project
operation and hundreds of foreign experts from over 50 countries,
who include representatives of foreign contractors, and managerial
and technical staff employed by the contractors, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
According to Cui Xuewen, director of the company's personnel
division, since the project was formally launched in 1993 a
series of training courses on project supervision and the English
language have been held, with the number of trainees exceeding
500. Meanwhile, over 800 students of hydrology have been trained
there.
</P>
<P>
To further improve the expertise of Chinese managers the
corporation has sent 89 people to be trained abroad, and 11 have
been sent to study the International Engineering Management
Speciality at Tianjin University, Cui added.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the corporation has drawn up a plan this year to
train 180 medium- and high-level managerial experts in the coming
five years, and to invest one million yuan for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Huanzhang, director of the company's publicity
division, 70 percent of the 200-plus staff in the corporation have
a higher-education background. 
</P>
</TEXT>
