<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zoo Keepers Look for Father of Panda Cub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zoo keepers in the Chinese
capital are still unsure which giant panda is the father of a baby
panda, even though the cub is now more than six months old.
</P>
<P>
They said that there are "three possible fathers".
</P>
<P>
"It's very important for us to make it clear, because the mother
panda, 'Le Le', mated with two male pandas and was artificially
inseminated before she gave birth to the baby," explained Zong
Ying, director of the Beijing Zoo.
</P>
<P>
"If we know exactly which one is the cub's real father we can
avoid inbreeding among pandas in future, and the quality of panda
reproduction will be improved," said Wang Changhai, a panda raiser
at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is one of the most endangered species on
earth. There are only some 1,000 pandas, most of them living in
west China's Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
<P>
A mature female panda can become pregnant once a year if she
can successfully mate with a male panda during the
three-to-five-day oestrus period, and can produce one or two
babies.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate of successful breeding remains fairly low and
depends largely on artificial insemination, the technique of which
has become well developed in China.
</P>
<P>
"Le Le" gave birth to two cubs on October 4 last year, but
only one cub survived.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
