<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Atop Mubarak Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The stalemated Middle East peace
process tops the agenda of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's tour
of three Gulf countries, a Kuwaiti official told the Egyptian
Voice of Arab radio today.
</P>
<P>
Suleyman Majid Al Shaheen, Kuwaiti Foreign Undersecretary,
said that Mubarak, accompanied by several ministers and aides,
held brief talks Saturday with Kuwait's Amir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed
al-Sabah on the setbacks in the Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
It was Mubarak's fourth visit to Kuwait since the 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak started his three-nation Gulf tour Saturday which has
already taken him to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia. He is scheduled to
visit the United Arab Emirates later today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who is accompanying the
president, said Saturday that the current tour is "the beginning
of other Arab contacts and tours to coordinate stances with
regard to the circumstances the Middle East area is passing
through."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif said Mubarak's
visit took place against the backdrop of the vacillating situation
in the Middle East, which called for consultations among the Arab
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks groundded to a halt last month after Israel
started construction of a new Jewish settlement on Har Home in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mubarak told Egyptian television that he opposed
holding an Arab summit at present for fear it could further
complicate the peace talks by taking collective measures against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Egypt was ready to host a summit meeting among Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat and Jordan's King Hussein if Israel could
stop building settlements on occupied Arab lands, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's renewed diplomatic drive came a day after the U.N.
General Assembly voted 134-3 to demand an immediate halt to the
Har Homa housing project and an end to all forms of support for
Israel's settlement activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
