<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia's Election Campaign Kicks Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's three political
parties -- the ruling party Golkar, the United Development Party
(PPP) and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) -- today began
their election campaigns in different areas throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
Massive gatherings of thousands of yelling, drum-beating and
horn-whistling political supporters became the main
characteristics of the 27-day nation-wide campaign which will run
until May 23.
</P>
<P>
During the campaigning, the three contenders will try to
attract as many as 124 million registered voters in the general
election scheduled for May 29.
</P>
<P>
The three contestants will also campaign through the
state-owned television and radio stations. The 30-minute
pre-recorded speeches will be aired and relayed by the five
private television stations and radio stations across the country,
every day starting 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The General Election Institute has introduced the zoning system
in this year's election, the seventh held since independence. Each
political party is obliged to conduct its campaign in two
specially designed regions each day.
</P>
<P>
The regulation divides the country into six campaign regions:
Region I is for provinces in Sumatra; Region II for provinces in
Java; Region III fro provinces in Bali, West and East Nusa
Tenggara and East Timor; Region IV for provinces in Kalimantan;
Region V for provinces in Sulawesi; And Region VI for the
provinces of Maluku and Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
Under Indonesia's current rules of campaigning, no political
party is allowed to question the state ideology, Pancasila, nor
the 1945 constitution, nor to damage another parties' reputation.
</P>
<P>
A party is allowed to promote its programs in connection with
national development. It could say good things about itself, but
it is forbidden to say anything bad about the government, its
policies or its officials.
</P>
<P>
The government also banned motor parades and marches during the
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
Golkar, which hopes to win 350 seats, or 70 percent of the
500-seat House of Representatives (DPR) during the election, today
started its campaign in Java, Maluku and Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Jakarta, the atmosphere was heating as
ten massive gatherings were held in five districts of the city,
but the situation was firmly controlled and there was no report of
any incidents till now.
</P>
<P>
The two minority parties -- PPP and PDI began their campaign
separately in other areas out of Java.
</P>
<P>
PPP's Chairman Ismail Hasan Metareum started his campaign this
morning in Medan, North Sumatra. He said his party will fight for
democratization, social justice and rights.
</P>
<P>
Golkar Chairman Karmoko started his campaign in Lebak regency,
West Java, in the morning, and in the afternoon, he arrived in
Jakarta with several prominent Golkar members including cabinet
ministers to continue his campaign.
</P>
<P>
PDI's Chairman Soerjadi, who made a speech on the radio this
morning, campaigned in Pontianak, West Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
All the three parties are currently eyeing the 425 available
seats in DPR. Under Indonesia's political system, the DPR has 500
seats in which 75 are observed for the Armed Forces (ABRI) whose
members do not vote. ABRI's number of seats have been reduced by
25 in comparison to the 1992 general election.
</P>
<P>
All the three contestants, which had filed a total of 2,285 DPR
candidates, are mainly eyeing votes in Java, Indonesia's most
crowded island. Java houses 70 percent of the registered voters.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 general election, the ruling Golkar lost 17 seats,
most of them in Java. The party is now struggling to regain the 17
seats it lost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
