<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Has No Expectation from EU: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran has no any expectation
from the European Union (EU) countries and they can do whatever they
like, Iranian foreign minister Ali Akbar Velayati said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Velayati said that Iran wants to have
good relations with European countries "but what is more important
for us is the observance of our principles in the foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister made the statement on the eve the
ministerial meeting of the European Union member nations,
scheduled to be held in Brussels on April 29.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question raised by Xinhua, Velayati said that "our
foreign relations is (are) not limited to our relations with
European countries."
</P>
<P>
He said: "We can procure our needs from different countries
and sell them too. We have a vast network of ties with 140
other countries. We also have 136 embassies and councillor
offices."
</P>
<P>
"We have good relations with many countries such as China,
Russia, Southeast Asia, Japan, Canada and others," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Iran welcomes the initiative of good ties
by all countries, including EU, so long as they are based on
mutual respect and interest.
</P>
<P>
The April 10 Berlin court verdict, which implicated top
Iranian leaders with an assassination of four Kurdish opposition
leaders in Mykonos restaurant in Berlin five years ago, sparked a
fierce diplomatic battle between Iran and Germany. About 400
extremist Muslim students even threatened to seize the Germany
Embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had recalled their ambassadors and expelled
four diplomats each other. All EU member countries, except
Greece, have recalled their ambassadors in protest against the
alleged involvement of Iranian leaders in the Mykonos case.
</P>
<P>
All foreign ministers of EU member countries are going to
meet and iron out a joint and unified policy toward Iran at
the ministerial meeting to be held Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister said "our relations with other
countries are based on mutual respect and mutual interest. We
don't agree with unilateral relations. We believe in this very
important principle as mentioned in the Vienna Convention."
</P>
<P>
"That means absence of the interference in the internal
affairs of each other. We know that the dual containment
policy which was imposed on us by the Americans is now
defeated," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
