<HEADLINE> Moscow, Minsk, Kiev Mark Anniversary of Chernobyl Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia, Ukraine and Belarus today
marked the 11th anniversary of the Chernobyl nuclear accident, the
worst nuclear disaster in the world.
</P>
<P>
April 26 is "a day of great grief for mankind," said Yeltsin in
a message to the nation in commemoration of the accident which
cost thousands of lives and contaminated a vast area of land.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin called for help of the whole society for the victims of
the disaster and promised that the government would continue to
care for those who suffered.
</P>
<P>
Russian Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov laid a wreath at a
cemetery in Moscow today where some victims of the accident were
buried.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Ukraine, hundreds of workers at the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant stood in silence at noon today to remember
those who died in the accident, while thousands gathered in the
capital of Kiev for ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
In Belarus, downwind from Chernobyl, about 20,000 people
marched through the capital of Minsk.
</P>
<P>
The explosion of the 4th reactor of Chernobyl nuclear power
plant in 1986, resulting from violation of operational regulations
of the installation, forced the evacuation of more than 1 million
people around.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 people in former Soviet republics have died
from radiation doses received in the Chernobyl blast.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has promised to completely close down the power plant,
located 130 kilometers to the north of Kiev and not far from the
southern border of Belarus, by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
