<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Cabinet Approves State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian cabinet has approved a
83.3-billion-pound (24.5 billion U.S. dollars) budget for the
fiscal year of 1997-98 and the Fourth Five-Year National
Development Plan (July 1997-July 2002), the Egyptian Gazette
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The budget expenditure was 7.5 percent larger than the 77.5
billion pounds (22.8 billion dollars) for the current fiscal year,
said Talaat Hammad, cabinet affairs and follow-up minister, after
the meeting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 1997-98 budget has been designed to increase total
government expenditure from 77.5 billion Egyptian pounds (22.8
billion dollars) to 81.1 billion pounds (23.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Expenditure in social services (health, education, social
insurance, etc,) is planned to reach 29.8 billion pounds (8.8
billion dollars), taking up 36.7 percent of the government
spending.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the general revenues in the new budget total 76.4
billion pounds (22.5 billion dollars) against 71.1 billion pounds
(20.9 billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A total of 58 billion pounds (17 billion dollars) will be
invested in the country in 1997-98, the first year of the
five-year plan, to help reduce unemployment through creating
540,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the first year of the 1997-2002 national
development plan targets a 6.3 percent growth in gross domestic
product (GDP), up from 5.7 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to raise the citizen's per capita income to 4,463
pounds (1,313 dollars) from 4,377 pounds (1,287 dollars) in the
1996-97 fiscal year and boost the investment to 58 billion pounds
(17.06 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget, which falls within a landmark
blueprint to achieve an annual growth rate of 7 percent over the
next two decades, is aimed at achieving a comprehensive development,
encouraging investment and completing the economic reform.
</P>
<P>
The budget will be presented to the parliament by May 1 for approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
