<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak concluded a visit to Saudi Arabia today after holding
talks with Saudi King Fahd on the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuwait News Agency reports from Jiddah, Saudi
Arabia, Mubarak's talks with Fahd also covered bilateral
relations and the latest Arab and International developments.
</P>
<P>
The visit came within the framework of consultations between
the leaders of the two countries to map out an Arab position in
times of crisis, diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak, who last visited the Kingdom in August 1996,
was accompanied by foreign and information ministers and other
top government officials.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving in Jiddah, Mubarak stopped in Kuwait and held
talks with Amir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said Mubarak's undeclared visit to Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia was aimed to discuss the Arab developments,
especially the stalemated Middle East Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
His tour was designed to gain Arab support for an expanded or
mini summit to salvage the peace process from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mubarak said that he was ready to hold a mini-summit
grouping Syria, Jordan, the Palestinian National Authority and
Egypt to work out a stance parallel to the Israeli initiative to
promote peace.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, however, said a pan-Arab summit was not appropriate
for the time being.
</P>
<P>
Israel's continued moves with the construction of a new Jewish
settlement in Har Homa in East Jerusalem last month brought
the Middle East peace process to a standstill and triggered Arab
and world anger.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries decided to freeze all normalization
process with the Jewish state in a foreign ministers' meeting
in Cairo afterwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
