<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 07:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Therapy for Diabetics with Gangrene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Diabetics whose blood
circulation is so poor that their feet develop gangrene and
osteomyelitis and who consequently face limb amputation, can be
helped by fly maggots that eat away necrotic tissue, allowing
new layers of healthy tissue to cover the wound.
</P>
<P>
This unaesthetic but potentially successful therapy offered to
patients at Israel's Hadassah-University Hospital in Jerusalem
by parasitologists at the affiliated Hebrew University Hadassah
Medical School, was reported on the latest issue of Harefuah, a
journal of the Israel Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
The team, headed by parasite expert Kosta Muncuoglu, provided
doctors with larvae of the sheep blowfly, Phoenicia Sericata,
for treatment of five elderly diabetic patients whose gangrene
had not improved with antibiotic therapy.
</P>
<P>
Despite severe pain and the danger of blood poisoning, the
patients refused to have their limbs amputated, then they
nevertheless agreed to undergo maggot therapy twice a week.
</P>
<P>
Sterile larvae were applied to the wound and replaced about
twice a week, and in the most seriously affected patient, the
blackened, necrotic tissue around the toes and on the soles of
the feet detached from the healthy tissues at the end of four
months.
</P>
<P>
During the last three months, the maggots had removed the
remaining infected tissue and the pain disappeared, as the
patient was able to walk without discomfort.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the other patients, who had relatively superficial
gangrene, completed their therapy in a month.
</P>
<P>
The idea of using maggots to remove gangrenous tissue did not
originate at Hadassah, and the possibility was first observed by
Napoleon's chief military physician and than later by the chief
medical officer in the United States Civil War.
</P>
<P>
It was used until the 1950s, but when antibiotics and
surgical techniques became available, the use of fly larvae was
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
With the development of bacterial strains resistant to
antibiotics, doctors thought of returning to the parasitic
technique, but only those patients who did not respond to any
other therapy.
</P>
<P>
It can also be used for burns, scores, chronic bone infection
and pus-filled boils.
</P>
<P>
The main shortcomings of using maggots are the psychological
and aesthetic problems of patients feeling they are being "eaten
alive" by parasites, but the larvae's freedom of action is
limited by bandages, and medications reduce the itching of the
bite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0080 </DOCNO>
