<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders probe of Alleged Abduction of Fisherman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today ordered cabinet members to look into and take appropriate
actions on the alleged abduction of Filipino fishermen by
Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, the presidential office said
Ramos has asked Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa, and Interior Secretary Robert Barbers
to submit a process report not later than Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The office said that on April 14, Malaysian natives at Barque
Island complained of being robbed of three motorboat engines,
cash, and valuables by Filipino pirates.
</P>
<P>
On that day, it said, an undetermined number of Malaysians,
aboard a vessel that "closely resembled the Malaysian naval patrol
craft," entered Philippine waters and docked at Mangsee Island,
Balabac, Palawan Province.
</P>
<P>
On the following day, the intruders rounded up several
residents in the islet and forced seven fishermen, including a
10-year-old boy, to board their own five motorboats, the office
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Malaysians then tied these motorboats in a row and towed
them to Malaysian waters," it said.
</P>
<P>
The abducted Filipino fishermen are now detained by Malaysian
authorities at Kudat, Malaysia, and are being forced to confess to
the robbery, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The office quoted Palawan police and military authorities as
saying that the Malaysians bagged the wrong guys, adding that the
Filipino pirates who raided Barque Island were residents of nearby
Barangay Indalawan, also in Balabac, Palawan.  
</P>
