<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABC of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (47-48) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Following is an ABC of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (47-48) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: How will the Chief Executive and public servants of
the Hong Kong SAR be dealt with in case of their corruption and
graft?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Laws and regulations previously in force in Hong Kong
will be retained except those that contravene the Basic
Law. Therefore, existing anti-corruption regulations in Hong Kong
will continue to be employed to prosecute and punish public
servants who violate such regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to article 47 of the Basic Law, the Chief Executive
must be a person of integrity, dedicated to his or her duties, and
must, on assuming office, declare his or her assets. Article 73
spells out procedures for impeaching the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
Question: After 1997, can judicial organs in Hong Kong
establish juridical relations with their inland counterparts?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The relationship between Hong Kong and inland judicial
organs will be one of non-subordination and
co-operation. According to Article 95 of the Basic Law, the Hong
Kong SAR may, through consultations and in accordance with law,
maintain juridical relations with judicial organs of other parts
of the country; and they may render assistance to each
other. Needless to say, all these procedures must be conducted in
accordance with law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
