<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Get Jail Terms For Cheating Banks of Billions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Five men, two Japanese, two
from Taiwan and one Singaporean, who tried to cheat three foreign
banks here of billions of dollars in two months, had received jail
terms ranging between four and five years, the Sunday Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The five had conspired with Sadako Okada, an elderly Japanese
woman who self-claimed to be the illegitimate daughter of the late
Japanese Emperor Hirohito.
</P>
<P>
Between January and February last year, they tried to open
accounts at three foreign banks here with a forged Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank draft worth 1.27 trillion Japanese yen, amounting to more
than 9.7 billion US dollars at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The banks targeted by the group were the Republic National Bank
of New York, American Express Bank, and the Union Bank of
Switzerland. When they met the officers of the banks, they
introduced Okada as a Japanese royal to facilitate the cashing of
the bank draft.
</P>
<P>
However, the extraordinarily large amount made the banks
suspicious. After their own checks, the banks discovered that the
bank draft was forged. They then reported to the authorities and
the Commercial Affairs Department of Singapore arrested all six
members of the group at one of the banks in March last year.
</P>
<P>
Last August, District Judge Jasvender Kaur of Singapore sent
Okada to jail for one and a half years. But the Japanese woman
died of natural causes on March 11 this year, two days before she
was due to be released from the Changi Women's Prison.
</P>
<P>
After a 53-day hearing, District Judge Rahim Jalil found all
five men guilty on Saturday and he sentenced the two from Taiwan
to four years and a half in jail each on two charges of conspiring
to cheat. The two Japanese men were jailed for four years each on
two conspiracy charges of abetting Okada, while the Singaporean, a
bankrupt, received the heaviest sentence of five years' jail on
two charges of conspiring to cheat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
