<HEADLINE> Buoyant Trend on India Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE)
market showed a buoyant trend with the sensitive index rising
sharply by over 129 points during the week.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index rose by 103.27 points to 3,799.79 on
Monday and moved further upwards to close the week at 3,825.57 as
against the last weekend close of 3696.52, showing a net gain of
129.05 points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also shot up by 47.86 points to 1,637.94 at
the weekend from 1,590.08 in the previous weekend.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the US dollar index were quoted up at 364.77
and 169.88 at the close of the week compared with the last
Thursday's close of 354.74 and 164.97 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The market leader, Reliance Industries, shot up by 25.25 to
305.25. SBI (new) gained by 18.50 to 314.75, Tata Steel by 2.75 to
181.50 and MTNL by 17.75 to 292.75.
</P>
<P>
Strongly aided by hopes of political stability with the
assumption of office by the United Front government under new
prime minister I.K. Gujral which would facilitate the smooth
passage of the finance bill and the market-friendly budget for
1997-98 in the parliament session beginning from April 30, the
market sentiment generally remained firm on persistent buying
support from foreign institutional investors and bull operators.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's assurance that the economic reforms would
continue irrespective of political uncertainties provided fresh
impetus to the market.  
</P>
