<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Confident in Italy's Joining Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
today reaffirmed his confidence that Italy will join the launch of
the European single currency, the Euro, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Despite figures published in mid-week by the EU commission
suggesting that Italy might not qualify for joining the Euro,
Prodi declared in a newspaper interview, "We will succeed in
entering the Euro."
</P>
<P>
The EU commission put Italy's budget deficit for this year at
3.2 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP), which was 0.2
percent above the ceiling set in the Maastricht Treaty for the
entry of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Calling the EU commission's figure "technically unjustified",
Prodi said, "I cannot understand why the European Commission gave
us a ratio of deficit of GDP of 3.2 percent while others gave us
three percent."
</P>
<P>
Forecasts from the International Monetary Fund and the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development had
suggested that Italy would qualify for the Euro Launch.
</P>
<P>
The EU is targeting to launch the Euro by January 1, 1999. But
scepticism is growing over whether the deadline can be met as few
members have been able to fulfill the criteria set by the
Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
On the achievements of his 11-month administration, Prodi said,
"I would like to know what other countries have succeeded in
achieving an improvement like ours."
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded that Italy had to overcome a reputation
for economic unreliability.
</P>
<P>
On future structural reforms of the pension and welfare systems
which his government is aiming to achieve this year, Prodi noted,
"I have no intention of dismantling the welfare system."
</P>
<P>
He also rejected proposals raised by the center-right
opposition to form a broadly based coalition to take Italy into
the European Economic and Monetary Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
