<HEADLINE> Thailand to Support Myanmar's ASEAN Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Despite U.S. pressure to delay
admitting Myanmar into the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), Thailand will not be swayed, according to a Thai
government deputy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Tinakorn Kanasuta, deputy government spokesman for foreign
affairs, said on Saturday that Thailand will adhere to its
position to support Myanmar in becoming a member of ASEAN, because
the grouping has already made the decision.
</P>
<P>
At both the fifth ASEAN summit in Bangkok in 1995 and the
informal ASEAN summit in Jakarta in 1996, Thailand agreed in
principle to support Myanmar's entry as a full member of the
grouping, Tinakorn said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has decided that the three observer nations -- Cambodia,
Laos and Myanmar -- will join ASEAN together, and ASEAN foreign
ministers are scheduled to meet in late May in Malaysia to
consider if the three are all ready to join and a formal decision
is to be made in July.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said
the U.S. was trying to persuade ASEAN to reject Myanmar's bid to
become a full member on the grounds of its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Amnaj Chananwongse, another deputy spokesman for the
Thai government, insisted that Thailand has a "strong policy of
non-interference in the internal affairs of its neighboring
countries," adding that "Thailand must always be careful and
sincere in its relations" with its neighbors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
