<HEADLINE> China's Entry to WTO to Help Market Share of Import Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Market share of import
automobiles may rise again next year in China as the central
government is about to solve hurdles that have caused the slump in
demand, said an article in today's "China Daily Business Weekly".
</P>
<P>
China's probable entry into the World Trade Organization (WHO)
is also expected to improve the situation, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Hit by restricted demand, high tariffs and growing domestic
production, the share of imported automobiles has slumped to the
lowest level since the People's Republic of China was founded in
1949.
</P>
<P>
The market share of car imports this year may be lower than
last year's 14 percent, compared with an average of 48 percent
between 1991 and 1996, 61 percent in the 1980s, 38 percent in the
1960s and 1970s, and 82 percent in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
However, the needs among China's car buyers are widening, and
this is likely to increase demand for imported models, especially
in the coastal booming areas, said Chen Ping, vice-president of
the China Trading Center of Imported Automobiles, the country's
largest auto distribution network.
</P>
<P>
Chinese as well as foreign automotive executives said they
expect individuals' buying of cars in the country will further
increase as their incomes grow and the desire for efficiency is
amplifying.
</P>
<P>
More and more Chinese automotive experts are admitting that the
relatively slack domestic markets is in many ways due to high
costs and unsatisfactory quality.
</P>
<P>
Expecting more vehicles imports after China enters WTO, the
domestic industry is stepping up efforts to improve product
quality and variety, the article said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
