<HEADLINE> Courts in Shenzhen Handles More Economic Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Courts at various levels in
Shenzhen, a special economic zone in Guangdong Province, dealt
with a rising number of economic cases last year, a senior judge
said.
</P>
<P>
Reporting on the courts' work to the local legislature, Xu
Liangdong, president of the Intermediate People's Court of
Shenzhen, said that in 1996 the courts handled 6,282 economic
cases, an increase of 15.3 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The cases involved a total sum of 10.31 billion yuan (1.24
billion US dollars), up 60.5 percent over 1995, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the cases involved financial disputes, mainly
related to loans, fund-raising, securities and futures.
</P>
<P>
Judges were careful to avoid the loss of state assets when
handling 97 bankruptcy cases, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The courts dealt with 28.9 percent more cases involving real
estate and 62 percent more involving intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the courts cracked down harder on economic
crime, giving 282 criminals involved in such crime prison terms
longer than five years, and in some cases, the death penalty, Xu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
