<HEADLINE> Fujian to Open More Drug Rehabilitation Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Police officials in east China's
Fujian Province plan to set up drug rehabilitation centers in the
province's leading cities next year in an attempt to help addicts
kick their habit.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has ordered local police departments
in Fuzhou, which is Fujian's capital, Xiamen, Quanzhou and
Zhangzhou to open rehab centers before September.
</P>
<P>
Next year, such centers are to be established in Putian, Ningde
and Sanming cities, and also in other small cities and counties
which have a certain number of drug addicts, according to the
government order.
</P>
<P>
Local judicial departments will also be responsible for
establishing court-ordered rehab centers for drug users, who have
been put into reeducation-through-labor camps to be cured of their
addiction.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen, Fujian's economically-developed city, will open such a
center this year.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government also asked the Provincial Department
of Health and the Provincial Office of Narcotics Control to
examine voluntary rehab centers opened by hospitals and other
medical institutes.
</P>
<P>
Individuals are not allowed to provide rehabilitation service
and sell medicine used for detoxification.
</P>
<P>
Fujian currently has only three rehab centers, in Fuzhou,
Xiamen and Fuqing, which have offered rehabilitation service to
more than 3,800 substance abusers.
</P>
<P>
However, the province has been in great need of such facilities
with the rapid rise in drug users in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The number of drug addicts registered in government
institutions in the province has soared from 180 people in 1991 to
the current 4,000.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's decision is part of China's newest massive anti-drug
fight which is planned to last until September.
</P>
<P>
China currently reports a total of 520,000 drug addicts. Some
600 rehabilitation centers have been established across the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Calls for Enterprise Merger in Light Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's light industry should
improve its structure and become more competitive by merging large
enterprises and annexing weak ones, said a senior light industry
official.
</P>
<P>
The effort can help eliminate unnecessary construction and
establish an economy of scale in the industry, Hu Nan, director
general of the National Council of Light Industry's planning and
development department, was quoted by today's "China Daily" as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Light industry will give priority to leading companies in
various industrial sectors, provide financial support and
encourage them to annex inferior companies, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
It also will apply for state approval so more large enterprises
will be able to finance and float bonds and stocks, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
By merging large enterprises and annexing small and less
competitive companies, light industry is expected to create 100
large enterprise groups with more than two billion yuan (240
million US dollars) annual sales by 2000.
</P>
<P>
China's light industry has long been plagued with a poor
structure: construction of similar projects and wasting resources
because of low manufacturing technology.
</P>
<P>
For example, air conditioning companies used 33 percent of
their capacity in 1995. Plastics firms used 40.6 percent and
washing machine makers used 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Light industry is directly related to daily life and is
basically a processing industry. So many companies have blindly
invested in low technology projects without considering the whole
market and existing production capacity, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
The problem is particularly serious for breweries, leather
makers, paper mills and household ceramic makers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Equipment to Dominate Major Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- New power plants in China would
no longer use foreign 300,000- and 350,000-kw generators, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
China should develop its power industry on the basis of
domestic products and imports should be supplementary, China Daily
quoted Power Industry Minister Shi Dazhen as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, China may have to continue to import one million-kw
generators, for the country is unable to build such big machines,
Shi said.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders said 40 percent of the machine-building
industry's capacity for building major generators is idle because
of imports.
</P>
<P>
Analysts are optimistic about Chinese machinery because the
country's decision to withdraw preferential treatment for imported
equipment would prevent the import of too many major foreign
machines.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's 235 million-kw generating capacity, 80 percent
comes from domestically produced equipment. Of 300,000-kw or
higher generators, 50 percent were domestic products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
