<HEADLINE> Latin American Cultural Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
cultural, artistic, and entertainment events occurred in the last
few days:
</P>
<P>
Ruben Blades Interested in Producing Movies in Spanish
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Panamanian author and singer Ruben Blades announced
here his interest in producing movies in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
A singer and composer with several Grammy prizes, a
politician, former presidential candidate for the "Papa Egoro"
party in his country, Blades is searching new lodes.
</P>
<P>
The singer visited Costa Rica with a group of U.S. artists, to
participate in a series of activities in environment protection.
</P>
<P>
Ruben Dario Collection Inaugurated in Managua
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- First Lady of Nicaragua Maria Dolores Aleman,
daughter of President Arnoldo Aleman, inaugurated Wednesday,
International Day of the Book, the Ruben Dario Collection in the
National Palace of Culture.
</P>
<P>
The collection includes more than 4,000 works all related to
the life and works of the great Nicaraguan poet that made a
revolution in the world of Spanish literature.
</P>
<P>
Miss Aleman said it is necessary to promote love for culture
and the arts among the young, creating in them the habit of
reading and the love for books.
</P>
<P>
Frida Kahlo's Works To Be Exhibited in Santiago
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The first exhibition in Chile of the work of
Mexican painter Frida Kahlo will be inaugurated April 29, with
several original works and reproductions, photographs, and objects
of the daily life of the consecrated Mexican artist.
</P>
<P>
The show, titled "Passion for Frida," is a retrospective
exhibition with more than 500 pieces, shown before in New York,
Los Angeles, San Francisco, Sao Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Bogota, and
Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The 17th "The Best Books For Children 1997"
Exhibition will be inaugurated April 30 in Caracas to show the
most recent titles for children published in Spanish and as a
source of information for consumers here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which will last all the month of May.
</P>
<P>
This year the exhibition has 93 titles, published in 11
countries by 33 publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
Brazil Opens More Public Libraries
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil opened last year 50 public libraries in
several municipalities of the country.
</P>
<P>
Information provided by the Education Ministry shows that with
the program One Library For Each Municipality, launched in 1996,
the ministry spent more than 2 million dollars to install the
public libraries in the whole country, especially in the north and
northeast regions.
</P>
<P>
Following its plan, the ministry will allocate more resources
to the program, which aims at installing about 100 public
libraries.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's University To Create "Octavio Paz" Cathedra
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The National Autonomous University of Mexico
(UNAM) will create the extraordinary cathedra "Octavio Paz," the
first to be instituted during the life of a writer for his
performance in the literary field.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Thursday by Juliana Gonzalez, director of
the UNAM'S School of Philosophy and Letters, the institution that
will be the venue of this cathedra, planned with the Fondo de
Cultural Economic publishing house. 
