<HEADLINE> Capture of Fishermen Causes Tension in Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The naval forces of Nicaragua,
Honduras and el Salvador are on alert because of a recent mutual
capture of fishermen among the three countries, a Nicaraguan
diplomats said here today.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the Honduran naval force captured four
Nicaraguan fishermen who were fishing in the Gulf of Fonseca on
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"This capture is a retaliation for the detention of 14 Honduran
pirates captured by the Nicaraguan navy days before in our
country's territorial waters," the source added.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan National Army captured four Honduran fishermen
on April 17 and nabbed 10 more three days later. The arrested have
been deported to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
In the morning of April 23, the coast guard of el Salvador
captured a Honduran-registered shrimp boat "Lady Barbara" and
its nine crew in Fonseca, a water area between Nicaragua, Honduras
and el Salvador.
</P>
<P>
This secret meeting was attended by the Honduran Navy Chief of
Staff Jesus Alberto Alvarez and his Nicaraguan counterpart Juan
Estrada Garcia started from Friday a secret emergency meeting
trying to end the military tension in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
