<HEADLINE> Favourites Take First-Day Matches in Ice Hockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 26 (Xinhua) -- All the favourites beat their
lower-ranked opponents to keep away upsets from the first-day
competition as the Ice Hockey World Championship started in Kurku,
Finland on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The winning stars blink for defending champions Czechs, Olympic
champions Sweden, 1994 world champions Canada and 1995 world
champions of Finland.
</P>
<P>
For the four matches unveiled of the day, Canada thrashed
Norway 7-0, Finland triumphed over France 6-1, Sweden outscored
Italy 5-3 and the Czechs rallied from behind to edge Germany 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Geoff Sanderson scored twice while Sean Burke and Rick
Tabaracci shared in the shutout for Canada over Norway, the
biggest world championship win since beating Austria 11-0 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish side had been anxious to take the opener as
president Martti Ahtisaari also presented, and they scored after
barely two minutes and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
Kai Nurminen and Olli Jokinen had two goals each to the delight
of the home audience in the new Hartwall Arena.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Vujtek set up two goals in the last 15 minutes to save
the day for the Czechs who rallied back for the hard-won victory.
</P>
<P>
And Jorgen Jonsson scored twice, including the clinching third
period goal to give Sweden a 5-3 win over Italy. 
</P>
