<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors in Brazil to Pay Less Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Brazil has reduced the tax
on financial operations to attract more foreign capital, said
Central Bank President Gustavo Loyola.
</P>
<P>
The tax was reduced Friday from 7 percent to 2 percent for
short-term capitals, while those of medium and long term were
tax exempted, Loyola as quoted by the press.
</P>
<P>
The government wants to prevent investors from taking their
capitals to the United States because of the recent rise in the
banking rates of interest. 
</P>
