<HEADLINE> UK Opposition Party to Have Landslide Victory, Polls Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Opposition Labor Party leader Tony
Blair looks set to enter Downing Street on May 1 with the largest
parliamentary majority held by any party since the Second World
War, opinion polls suggested.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls in three British Sunday newspapers showed Labor's
lead ranging from 15 to 24 points, implying a minimum Labor
representation in the 659-seat Commons of more than 400 MPs and a
parliamentary majority approaching 200.
</P>
<P>
An ICM poll in the Observer, the biggest poll ever conducted by
a newspaper, saw Labor unchanged on 47 percent compared to the
Conservatives 32 percent. The third largest party Liberal
Democrats had 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Observer poll, taken in 16 marginal constituencies held by
the Conservatives, suggested that eight cabinet ministers could
lose their seats to Labor, which is out of power since 1979.
</P>
<P>
A MORI poll for the Sunday Mirror gave Labor a hefty 24-point
lead over the ruling Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
An NOP poll in the Sunday Times said a slight Conservative
revival in the past two weeks had come to a shuddering halt.
</P>
<P>
It put Labor 18 points ahead of the Conservatives, up four
points from last week and said that if the results were repeated
nationally Labor would win 422 seats in parliament compared to 165
for the Conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
