<DOCNO> XIE19970427.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- U.S. Assistant Secretary of Commerce Larry Irving
said today Washington would help American telecom companies do
business in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Leading a 33-strong delegation of officials and businessmen to
a telecommunications conference to be held here from April 27 to
29, Larry said the U.S. government would try to bring the U.S. and
regional business partners to the negotiating table in the race for
contracts on multi-billion-dollar projects.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council states are expected to invest 13
billion dollars in telecommunications expansion projects,
according to the Inter-Arab Corporation for Investment Guarantee.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia and Cote d'Ivoire have signed agreements on
taxation and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by visiting Cote d'Ivoire Trade Minister
Nicolas Qouassi Acone, who met with Tunisian Prime Minister Hamed
Al Karoui today.
</P>
<P>
The both sides also explore the possibility of setting up air
and sea routes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Delegations from Singapore, Malaysia and China are
expected to arrive here soon to follow up agreements signed with
Egypt this month.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Al-Ganzouri returned home Wednesday from an
Asian tour of these countries, where he signed agreements on three
giant projects in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
A working group comprising some ministers and private sector
representatives would be formed soon to discuss details related to
the projects including the constructions of a port and free trade
zone.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt intends to present a working paper on 25 heavy
projects costing 15 billion dollars over a period of five years to
a meeting of donor countries in Paris on May 6.
</P>
<P>
The projects are aimed at improving services such as education,
health and drinking water supply to villages by the year 2000,
Minister of Public Business Sector and Minister of State for
Administrative Development Atef Ebeid said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Trade between Spain and the United Arab Emirates
in 1996 reached 365 million dollars, a 43 percent increase over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Spain imports from the Gulf state gas, garment, cotton and
machinery, while exporting to that country machinery, ceramic
tiles, furniture, cars, spare parts, steel and aluminium,
according to Gulf News today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
