<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Vows to Remove Land mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee
of Red Cross today called for a global ban on the production,
stockpiling, transfer and use of all anti-personnel mines, saying
that mines are increasingly used to terrorize civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
According to the Red Cross mission to the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), some 120 million active mines are scattered
in over 70 countries, one for every 16 children or 48 human
beings on the planet.
</P>
<P>
The countries infested with land mines include Angola,
Mozambique, Somalia and Sudan in Africa, Cambodia, Afghanistan,
Viet Nam and Iraq in Asia and Bosnia and Croatia in Europe and
others.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross said mines are indiscriminate in terms of target
and time. They go on killing and maiming soldiers and civilians,
men and women, adults and children alike, decades after the
fighting has ended.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 800 people were killed and 1,200
maimed every single month, which means one victim every 20
minutes. Many mine victims, usually civilians, never receive any
medical care and half of all victims are believed to die within
minutes of the blast.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the mines are increasing every year on the
planet with each year some 100,000 mines removed but two million
more planted.
</P>
<P>
It is a formidable work to clear mines on the planet.
According to the Red Cross, mines cost 3 to 30 U.S. Dollars each,
however, clearing a mine costs 50 times as much.
</P>
<P>
Removing the world's 120 million active mines could cost up to
33 billion U.S. Dollars. At current rates of progress, it would
take 1,100 years to clear the entire world of mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
