<HEADLINE> British Airways Refuses to Share Luggage Belt with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The British Airways today refused
to share the luggage belt with Air Algeria in a terminal of the
Roissy-Charles de Gaulles airport of Paris, and transported 450 of
its passengers by Euro-star train from Paris to London.
</P>
<P>
The action by British Airways is apparently a surprise for
French officials, who said that London airports have never
separated Air Algeria from other air companies.
</P>
<P>
Citing security reasons, the British Airways said that it is
resorting to legal action to pressure the authorities in charge of
of airports of Paris to separate it from Air Algeria, which
resumed its Algiers-Paris flight on Friday after a two-year
suspension.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of British Airways said that his company today also
transferred two of its passenger planes to the Orly airport to
avoid using the same luggage belt with Air Algeria.
</P>
<P>
He said that Air Algeria is a "high risk company" which can
be targeted by terrorist attacks, and pointed out that Air Algeria
is separated from other air companies in Marseille airports.
</P>
<P>
The British Transport Secretary Sir George Young has also
written to his French counterpart Bernard Pons expressing his
concern.
</P>
<P>
But the French government said today that all security
arrangements have been made to guarantee the security of all air
companies after Air Algeria resumed its flight from Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
