<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-26 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Criticizes EU for Siding with German Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran has stepped up criticism of
the European Union (EU) for backing a German court ruling three
days ahead of an EU meeting to review relations with the Islamic
Republic.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
today, Tehran sent a letter Friday to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan, condemning the EU position as "harmful to the peace and
security of the world."
</P>
<P>
The German court ruled on April 10 that the Iranian leadership
was behind the 1992 killing of four Kurdish dissidents in
Berlin. Tehran has strongly denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
Most EU countries recalled their ambassadors from Tehran for
consultations and froze critical negotiations with Iran shortly
after the court verdict was handed down.
</P>
<P>
The letter, signed by Iran's deputy representative at the
United Nations Majid Takhtravanchi, said the court ruling was
"baseless and impudent."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the EU countries will meet in Luxembourg to assess
their policies toward Iran, which was believed to have tried to
maintain good relations with the EU in the wake of U.S. sanctions
against the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
Neither the EU countries seemed ready to give up their
important market shares in Iran. Berlin has declared that it
remains opposed to efforts to isolate Iran despite the recent
tension in their relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
