<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen Passes Away (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen for a long time held leading posts in both
the Party and the state after the founding of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
In early days of New China, he was member of the Central
People's Government, Deputy Director of the Political and Legal
Affairs Committee of the Government Administration Council and
head of the Central Political and Legal Affairs Leading
Group. From 1954 onward, he served as Vice-chairman of the
Standing Committee of the First, Second and Third National
People's Congress (NPC) and Vice-Chairman of the Second, Third and
Fourth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC). At the Eighth National Congress
of the CPC and its first Plenum held in 1956, he was elected
member of CPC Central Committee, member of its Political Bureau
and member of the CPC Central Committee Secretariat, in which he
assisted Comrade Deng Xiaoping who took overall charge of the
Secretariat. He served concurrently as Secretary of the Beijing
Municipal Party Committee shortly before the peaceful liberation
of Beijing. He became Mayor of Beijing in 1951 and held the post
until May 1966.
</P>
<P>
In the 17 years after the founding of the People's Republic of
China, Comrade Peng Zhen, as a member of the leadership team of
the Party and the State headed by Comrade Mao Zedong, exerted all
his efforts and contributed remarkably to building of the Party,
political power and the economy as well as the work of political
and legal affairs, united front work, ideological and theoretical
work, science, education and culture, foreign affairs, and
construction and development of the Chinese capital.
